"18\" valign=\"top\">&#10;  <p class=\"MsoNormal\">T</p>&#10;  </td>&#10; </tr>&#10; <tr>&#10;  <td width=\"19\" valign=\"top\">&#10;  <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><u>7</u></p>&#10;  </td>&#10;  <td width=\"18\" valign=\"top\">&#10;  <p class=\"MsoNormal\">5</p>&#10;  </td>&#10;  <td width=\"18\" valign=\"top\">&#10;  <p class=\"MsoNormal\">6</p>&#10;  </td>&#10; </tr>&#10;</tbody></table>&#10;&#10;<p class=\"MsoNormal\">&#160;</p>&#10;&#10;<p class=\"MsoNormal\">&#160;</p>&#10;&#10;<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">.\'. Option &#34;D&#34;&#10;only represents DOG EAT EGG .</p></div><div><p class=\"MsoNormal\"></p>&#10;&#10;<p class=\"MsoNormal\"></p></div>', '', '0', '2020-03-17 00:00:00', '2020-03-17 00:00:00', 1),
(1613, 157, 178, 'Find the numberof 3 digit natural numbers\nwhich are divisible by 6', '', 'top', '151', '150', '152', '149', 'B', 178, 'D', '<font face=\"Arial\" size=\"3\"><b>(B)</b></font><div><span>Three digit natural numbers are from 100 to 999.</span><br></div><div>&#10;&#10;<p class=\"MsoNormal\">In between these numbers,</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">First number divisible by 6 is 102<br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Last number divisible by 6 is 996<br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">l=996, a=102, d=6<br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">.\'. Number of 3 digit natural numbers divisible BY 6<br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">$$=n=\\frac{l-a}{d}+1$$<br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">$$=\\frac{996-102}{6}+1=\\frac{894}{6}+1$$<br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">= 149 + 1 = 150</p>&#10;&#10;</div>', '', '0', '2020-03-17 00:00:00', '2020-03-17 00:00:00', 1),
(1614, 157, 179, 'What is the probability that a leap year selected\nat random will contain 53 Sundays ?', '', 'top', '<font face=\"Arial\" size=\"3\">$$\\frac{2}{7}$$</font><br>', '$$\\frac{3}{7}$$', '$$\\frac{4}{7}$$', '$$\\frac{5}{7}$$', 'A', 179, 'D', '<font face=\"Arial\" size=\"3\"><b>(A)</b></font><div><p class=\"MsoNormal\">There are 366 days in a leap year</p>&#10;&#10;<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Out of these, there are 52 Sundays</p>&#10;&#10;<p class=\"MsoNormal\">The remaining 2 days may be</p>&#10;&#10;<p class=\"MsoNormal\">{(Sunday, Monday), (Monday, Tuesday),&#160;<span>(Tuesday, Wednesday),(Wednesday,&#160;</span><span>Thursday), (Thursday, Friday), (Friday,&#160;</span><span>Saturday), (Saturday, Sunday)}</span></p>&#10;&#10;<p class=\"MsoNormal\">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; .\'. &#160;n(S) = 7</p>&#10;&#10;<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Out of these, there are only 2 possibilities to be a Sunday.</p>&#10;&#10;<p class=\"MsoNormal\">(i.e) {(Sunday, Monday), (Saturday, Sunday)}</p>&#10;&#10;<p class=\"MsoNormal\">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; n(E) = 2</p>&#10;&#10;<p class=\"MsoNormal\">$$\\therefore \\text { Probability, }&#10;\\mathrm{P}(\\mathrm{E})=\\frac{\\mathrm{n}(\\mathrm{E})}{\\mathrm{n}(\\mathrm{S})}=\\frac{2}{7}$$<br></p></div>', 'uploads/52ce4045d6fac122d9b9116ed017befd.jpg', 'top', '2020-03-17 00:00:00', '2020-03-17 00:00:00', 1);
